{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17620498","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17620498"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:44:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:44:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16632"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16632","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16632"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.02,0.05,0.86,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9323"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67121"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9323","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9323"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16632"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52577"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5312"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22096"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22456"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67121","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67121"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman requests non-hormonal contraception at her local family planning clinic. She is interested in getting a copper intrauterine device.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of copper intrauterine devices?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Prevents ovulation by suppressing hormones","Induces endometrial atrophy","Blocks fallopian tubes mechanically","Creates a spermicidal inflammatory environment","Thickens cervical mucus"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary mechanism of action of copper intrauterine devices is that they \u003Cstrong\u003Ecreate a spermicidal inflammatory environment\u003C/strong\u003E. The copper ions released from the device trigger a sterile inflammatory reaction that is toxic to sperm, preventing fertilisation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms are explained below:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrevents ovulation by suppressing hormones\u003C/strong\u003E: copper intrauterine devices are non-hormonal and have no effect on ovulation or the hormonal cycle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInduces endometrial atrophy\u003C/strong\u003E: while copper devices may alter the endometrium, they do not cause atrophy as hormonal methods might.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks fallopian tubes mechanically\u003C/strong\u003E: the device remains within the uterine cavity and does not extend into or obstruct the fallopian tubes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThickens cervical mucus\u003C/strong\u003E: this is a mechanism seen with progesterone-containing contraceptives, not copper devices.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe copper ions also directly impair sperm function by reducing motility and viability. Additionally, the inflammatory environment can prevent implantation by altering the endometrial environment, though this is a secondary mechanism.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Copper intrauterine devices work primarily by creating a sterile inflammatory response that is toxic to sperm and prevents fertilisation.","Copper ions released from the device interfere with sperm motility and viability.","Copper intrauterine devices can also prevent implantation by altering the endometrial environment."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52577"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16632"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52577","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52577"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-03T15:30:17+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-03T15:31:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9323"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67121"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null